description.text:
This two piece device allows you to get a firm hold on any type of textile without puncturing them. The first part of the device, which we will call the lock (shown in blue), fits closely into the base, which we will call the star because of its resemblance to a ninja throwing star (shown in red). This device has numerous useful applications around the home no matter where you live. The project webpage is here
  • Stretcher -?? 6 fasteners, a blanket and 2 poles
  • Hammock - 2 fasteners and a blanket
  • Emergency Tent -?? 4 fasteners and a plastic sheet or tarp
  • Greenhouse or row guard - Use a number of fasteners and clear plastic to create a greenhouse
  • Food transport - Use some form of fabric and 4 fasteners to make flexible box for carrying things like vegetables
  • Improved Tarps:
    • You can use a fastener to fix a grommet that has popped out of a normal tarp.
    • You can also use a number of fasteners to join multiple tarps together into a bigger tarp
    • You can create a custom waterproof cover
    • You can use the fasteners to hold the tarp in a custom way for another function -?? such as rain water collection or roof leak or boat protector.

To Make:
The STL files for printing both the star and the lock are available here and can be printed out of various materials on an open source rapid prototyper like the RepRap. To Use:
  • Wrap the lock in the fabric with its flat side touching the fabric.
  • Push the lock and the fabric through the hole in the star.

  • Turn the lock piece 90 degrees and pull into place (as shown assembled in Figure 1).

    • To take the fastener off just follow steps 1 through 3 in reverse.
    • Both the lock and the star have multiple holes that can be used either with tie lines or nails depending on your application. Suggestions for improvement always welcome.

remixed_from.title: E3D v6 Compact Extruder for i3 Rework

description.text: Remix of the Spritztruder by Kitemare, for i3 Rework. I also used a modified idler from the compact E3D extruder by Mak-a-Face. Modified to have better support for drive gear. Also uses typical herringbone gears from greg's accessible extruder, so hopefully is a bit easier to incorporate into existing systems. Also modified to fit larger capacity syringes - 30ml ones by Terumo (from eBay), have OD of 25mm and ID of 22.5mm. I tested Kitemare's Spritztruder and found the gear ratio to be OK when using M221 s1 in marlin to set the extrusion multiplier as 1%. It's a bit of a bad fix, but works OK for now, and I'd rather this that fiddling around with lots of gears to get a better ratio. You also need to fit a thermister to avoid thermal errors - use m302 to allow cold extrudes. I haven't carried out much testing, but wanted to share anyway. I'll be carrying out some more tests using a clay mix over the next few weeks. This is quite thick, so requires a really high pressure to push through the syringe. I imagine most other pastes (chocolate, sugar, etc) will be fine.

The plunger drive gear is held in place and secured by using a chamfered M8 bolt. You have to take ~1.5mm from one side, and ~2.5mm from the other side with a file. Use a vice and a good file to get a nice flat chamfer on either side of the bolt. I haven't tested much, but this should take the high load required to push paste through. BOM:
2no. M3x50
4no. M3 washers
2no. idler springs
1no. M3x30
2no. M3x40
5no. M3 nuts
1no. M8 Chamfered bolt
6no. M8 washers
1no. M8 nut
2no. 608 bearings
1no. M4x20 rod
1no. 624 bearing

title: Flexy-Hand - Filaflex Remix
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text: This takes FDM printing with elastic filaments to the next level. An iteration of the original Flexy-Hand, whose fingers are optimised to be printed with elastic filaments. This version was printed with Skin I Filaflex, Skin II also available.

• Hidden finger hinges, it's all in the geometry.
  • Fingers compatible with the Flexy-Hand family.
  • Each finger and thumb is printed in one piece. Using CraftWare customisable supports.
  • Silent realistic articulation.
  • Two thumb angle variants.
  • Base mountable, can be used as a terminal device for an existing prosthesis.
    • Thanks to Jeff Erenstone of Performance Orthopedic Design for his recommendations and consultation along this design process. http://www.gyrobot.co.uk
    http://www.facebook.com/gyrobotuk

• Print the fingers in elastic filament (e.g. Filaflex) on their end like they are orientated in the STL file.

  • Print fingers with support to add stability. I used Craftware's customisable supports. Also reduce extrusion width and layer height until the thin skin covering the hinge areas have two complete perimeters.

  • Print the base hinges, then dab a glue to the hinge to keep attached to finger. I printed hinges with no infill and 3 perimeters (depends on scale) using Slic3r, this makes them nice and "spongy" adjust this if you want stiffer or more flexible hinges. The hinges at the base of the fingers are assembled a certain way round to aid finger return, please see section image to show this.

  • Print the bolt plug and bolt carrier in rigid material. The bolt carrier will benefit by printing the first few layers with the same coloured material as the hand to help concealment.

  • At 100% scale, use an M12 or industry standard 1/2" HEX headed screw/bolt to mount to prosthesis.

• Thread a tendon down the tip of the finger and immediately back out of the tip so that the tendon loops around the integral tie bar at the end of the fingertip. A small piece of wire (paperclip) bent into a hook is a useful tool for grabbing the tendon to pull back out again. Tie this tendon off and secure knot with Superglue.

  • A long stiff wire is good to send down the tendon channels first then attach the tendon to this wire to pull through to the base of the finger.

Because this is meant to keep things square, the 8mm is slightly undersized.  I recommend printing with 3 perimeters, and using a .312 (5/16") drill bit to open up the 8mm hole.  This will allow the part to press onto the rod and have a fighting chance of being square.

Looking for a quick solution to mount my iPhone 4 on my tripod I decided to make a quick release plate. My tripod came with a quick release plate so I took out my digital callipers and made several measurements. A few minutes later in Blender I had come up with the initial design. It is designed to hold the phone in place by friction, it doesn't need to be that sturdy as I don't intend moving the tripod with the phone in place that much.
It printed very well in translucent blue PLA 4043D but the walls on top were a little too thin which meant they drooped a bit. I have since redesigned it to make the walls about twice as thick, Skeinforge should add an infill.
I have included the paper measurements I've taken in case they are of any use to people. It also gives an insight into how I designed it.

Alter the design and print. This was designed for an iPhone 4 in a polycarbonate case and a Velbon DF-40 tripod. I'm not sure how standardised quick release plates are but I guess you will need to modify it to fit your specific tripod.

description.text: Yet another printed quadcopter. Explores same style as delta tricopter but this time as quad.

To be printed
===========
  • 2x base
  • 2x mirrored base (use base file and flip it in slicer)
  • 1x control deck
  • optionaly - side deck
    • Part list
    =======
  • printed parts
  • vibration dampers (4-8 pcs)
  • motors for 250 size racing quads (4 pcs) (such as DYS BE1806 2300KV)
  • 15A ESC (4pcs) (such as AfroSlim)
  • control board
  • 6 inch props (6030) - CW&CCW
  • R/C transmitter and receiver
  • M3 screws & lock nuts
  • ZIP ties
  • Battery (such as ZippyCompact 1800mAh) - check dimensions. It has to fit bellow main deck.
    • Assembly
    ========
  • use M3 screws to join all bases together (Hint: put them upside down on flat surface. Add a bit of hot glue between them. Screw them together while holding.)
  • add velcro strap for battery. Install controller on the control deck over the velcro.
  • if you want to use side deck(s) attach it (them) to the control deck
  • install vibradion dampers and join control deck with bases. The battery has to fit bellow control deck.
  • install motors and ESCs
  • add R/C
  • connect everything to control board
    • Notes:
  • The control deck can be installed in two positions (facing front or side). Choose what you like but remember to corectly rotate controller.
  • The motors form perfect square. Therefore "both" directions can be used as a front side (e.g. it could be bat or 8 from to view).

title: Quick access tool holder for Taz

description.text:
I like having my most used tools quickly accessible, and not taking up table space.  
This mounts in the upper-right corner of your Taz, squeezing securely into the channels of the frame.  The extra bit in the corner fits inside the Taz's triangle bracket, and keeps the whole thing from falling out.  
Most of the tools don't vibrate while the printer is operating, but the scraper tool does, so I added the little spring finger to its slot to keep it still.  
WARNING: if you print very tall parts (~>140mm), some allen keys or scrapers might hit the Z-carriage as it comes up during the print.

Installation require taking off the triangle bracket to get the extrusion inside of it.  Once the part is pushed all the way into the corner, the bracket can be easily screwed back on.  
The thickness of the bottom (wider) section is designed to fit securely into the frame channel to prevent vibrations, so you may have to chamfer the edges and/or push hard to get it in.

title: Bottle Cap Opener - Strong and Simple

description.text:
I posted this bottle cap opener design because I saw people with openers they said fail. Printed with 1.2mm walls, .2 layer height, and 28% infill, from Filiament OutletPLA and hatchbox brand PLA, 1.75 mm with a cold bed, I have tested both styles (Penny and no metal) on over 100 cap opens (I have a bottle capper for the standard 26mm caps, not a drinking problem :D ) and the results were:
The "no metal" had some scratches at the opening surface, but nothing significant, no cracks. This may not work as well with ABS, if someone would let me know...
The Penny version had scratches and a slight bend, but no signs of failure. (I like the no metal version more) I'm starting to sell these and bring in some cash for a decent product, feel free to slap another logo on top and sell them yourselves. All I ask then is that you comment and let me know how you do. Thanks!

For the penny version, use a 1/8" rivet, a #5 screw and nut, or an M3 screw (Pop and solid Rivets worked great)  
The pad on the top is for decoration, 58mm x 12mm and adhered with HMA or superglue/cyanoacrylate.  
The end now is designed to have a wire clasp pressed into it, but for a regular key ring, just drill it instead.  
I cannot break these on a bottle or by hand, as long as the printer make solid prints.  It can also be used to open pop tops  
This design keeps the bending moments in the printing plane, that way there is no layer to layer shear force anywhere on this.  The contact surface for the cap is also revolved so that way force is spread out along the entire width.

title: Hasselblad 500 EL/M Battery Door Lock Screw
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text: A replacement for the plastic screw-like part of a Hasselblad 500 EL/Ms battery door.

This was created by measuring and a lot of trial and error.
After my battery door was blasted off by a shorted battery adapter and the plastic screw thingy broke apart, I had to create a replacement.
Just print this part, remove the old knob by pulling on the small metal bar that goes through it and take all the metal parts off.
Then simply replace the plastic part from Hasselblad with your printed part. Printing for me worked best using a layer height of 0.2mm on the no-hole version.
The version with hole included might work on printers that have fans to allow for faster hardening of the material.
Without additional cooling the holes always collapsed - print the no-hole version and drill the hole afterwards with a drill press if you run into this problem.

description.text: Ever get your filament stuck in the "Makerbot Industries Filament Spindle MK1" while in the middle of a print?  Me too.  That is why I came up with the Filament Spindle Wedge.

Print the wedge 4 times and hot glue the item in each of the four corners of your  "Makerbot Industries Filament Spindle MK1" next to the spool.  There is a bit of a gap to compensate for a slight wobble in the spindle.  Be sure it goes smoothly before making the installation permanent.  If needed, use sandpaper to narrow down the curve.  I also played with the idea of using paper (magazine cover - thicker stock) to bridge the gap from the wedge to the spindle with minimal resistance.
Any suggestions would be welcomed. Hope this idea helps others.
